import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Playwright training — grimbergIT"
  description="Playwright workshops — cross-browser coverage and deeper context for teams that need it."
>
  <article class="surface">
    <p class="eyebrow">Workshop · 03</p>
    <h1>Playwright</h1>

    <p>
      Playwright fits teams who need cross-browser coverage, or where the boring plumbing — auth
      flows, network interception, tracing across contexts — has to be part of the design rather
      than fought against. The workshop starts with the primitives and moves quickly into real code
      against a real application.
    </p>

    <h2>What we cover</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        The Playwright programming model — architecture, primitives, and the parts that shape how
        you write tests.
      </li>
      <li>
        Multiple browsers, multiple contexts, and multi-user flows — the situations Playwright
        exists for.
      </li>
      <li>
        Network interception, route stubbing, and the tracing tools that make debugging cheap.
      </li>
      <li>Component and API test modes: when they replace an end-to-end, and when they don't.</li>
      <li>CI patterns for parallelism, shards, and staying under the flake threshold.</li>
      <li>
        For teams evaluating or migrating from another framework — where Playwright diverges, and
        how to think about the differences without turning it into a religious war.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Format</h2>
    <p>
      One day by default. Splittable into two half-days if the team's calendar prefers it. Also
      available as a multi-week cohort with homework in between. In-house or remote — either works.
    </p>

    <h2>What you leave with</h2>
    <p>
      A working test setup against your own application, the CI configuration to run it, and enough
      judgement about when to reach for Playwright vs. anything else that the next framework debate
      is a shorter conversation.
    </p>

    <p>
      <a href="/training/">← Back to training</a> ·
      <a href="/contact">Book a session →</a>
    </p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
